        Timing Your Brisbane Sale Around the Queensland School Year: How Families Calibrate Their Move
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        For family buyers, settling before term 1 is a powerful priority. Here is how the Queensland school calendar shapes buyer activity in Brisbane's inner east and how sellers can choose the right listing window.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>For families with school-age children, settling into a new home before the school year starts is a powerful priority. The disruption of mid-term moves, the desire to begin a new year settled in a new community, and the practical realities of catchment enrolment dates all push family buyers toward predictable activity windows. Sellers who understand these windows, who think about who their property is most likely to sell to, and who calibrate the listing date accordingly produce stronger results than sellers who pick a date based on personal convenience alone.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the Queensland school calendar, the windows of family-buyer activity, the optimal listing dates for family-targeted homes, the catchment factor in Brisbane's inner east, and the situations in which school timing matters less or not at all.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why school timing dominates family-buyer decisions</h2>
      <p>For a family with one or more school-age children, the question of when to move is rarely abstract. The children are enrolled or about to be enrolled at a specific school. The family wants to settle before term 1, ideally with at least a few weeks to unpack and walk the new commute. Mid-term moves are disruptive, often require uniform changes, lose social momentum for the children, and create logistical problems for parents. Family buyers therefore plan their property purchase backwards from the start of term 1, and that backward planning shapes the buyer pool in predictable ways across the year.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Queensland school calendar (state schools)</h2>
      <p>For Queensland state schools, the year is structured around four terms. Term 1 runs from late January to late March (approximately ten weeks). Term 2 runs from mid-April to late June. Term 3 runs from mid-July to mid-September. Term 4 runs from early October to mid-December. The summer holidays span from mid-December to late January, which is the longest break of the year and the period in which most family relocations actually take place. Independent and Catholic schools have similar but not identical calendars, with some variation at the start and end of terms. International schools and the small number of overseas-curriculum schools can sit on different calendars again.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The family-buyer activity peaks</h2>
      <p>Family buyer activity in Brisbane has two visible peaks across the year. The largest is October to November, when families are searching with the explicit intent to settle before term 1. The smaller secondary peak is March to May, when families look to move during the term 2 holidays in late June or early July, or where the term 1 deadline has passed and they are willing to move mid-year if the right property comes up. Activity drops noticeably in December and January as the holiday period absorbs attention, picks up again gradually through February as families either complete deferred searches or start a new search cycle, and quietens through the winter months of June and July. These rhythms are not absolute (every campaign has its own dynamics) but they are consistent enough that sellers ignore them at a cost.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The seller's optimal listing windows for a family-targeted home</h2>
      <p>For a property that is most likely to sell to a family, the strongest listing window is late September to mid-October. This captures the largest pool of pre-term-1 buyers, allows for a typical six to eight week campaign, gives time for inspection and finance, and leaves the buyer with settlement and moving completed during the summer holidays before term 1. The secondary window is late January to early March, which captures families who missed the spring rush, who relocated to Brisbane after the new year, or who are willing to enrol mid-year. Outside these two windows, the family buyer pool is thinner and the seller is competing for a more diverse buyer mix.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why other windows are less family-focused</h2>
      <p>December and January listings face holiday distractions, with many family buyers physically away from Brisbane and others mentally focused on Christmas. Winter listings in June and July face weaker activity overall, partly because the term 2 deadline has passed and partly because Brisbane's weather is not at its most flattering for outdoor inspections. Listings in early September can be tempting because they capture the start of spring, but the campaign is often too tight to settle a buyer in time for term 1, which softens the family component of the buyer pool. The general principle is that seasonal weather effects matter less than school calendar effects for family-targeted properties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The catchment factor in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>Many Queensland state schools operate catchment requirements: students must live within a defined geographic zone to be enrolled, particularly where the school is at or near capacity. In Brisbane's inner east, popular catchment schools such as Bulimba State School, Norman Park State School, Cannon Hill State School, and Carina State School have intense local demand from families who specifically need to be in catchment for enrolment. For a property that sits inside one of these catchment zones, the school timing effect is amplified, and buyer competition concentrates in narrow windows around the relevant enrolment cycle. Catchment-zone sellers who list in October typically experience stronger results than sellers of equivalent properties just outside the catchment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers in catchment areas should do</h2>
      <p>Include school catchment details prominently in marketing material. Confirm with the relevant school or via the EdMap catchment search tool that the property is genuinely in catchment, because catchment lines move and outdated assumptions are a common source of buyer disappointment. Where the home is inside a desirable catchment, lead with that fact in listing copy, in the agent's database email, and in inspection conversations. For an October launch, brief the agent that family buyers in catchment will dominate the early enquiry pool, and structure the campaign accordingly with a clear timeline for offers ahead of the November to early December settlement window.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling while your own children are in school</h2>
      <p>Many sellers also have children in local schools, and the question of when to sell becomes a personal one as well as a market one. The two common positions are: sell after the school year for continuity, accepting that the family-buyer pool may be thinner in summer; or sell before to relocate without mid-term disruption, which means a winter or early spring campaign in a quieter market. The right answer depends on the family's circumstances, the school the children are at, and whether the next home is in the same catchment or elsewhere. There is no universally correct answer, but sellers who think about it explicitly produce better outcomes than sellers who default to whichever window first feels convenient.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Private school families and broader catchments</h2>
      <p>Families targeting private schools (Anglican Church Grammar School, St Joseph's Nudgee College, Lourdes Hill, Loreto, etc.) are more flexible geographically than state catchment families. Their buyer pool may prioritise commute distance to specific schools rather than residence within a fixed zone. The buyer pool is therefore broader geographically and the seller's catchment leverage is lower, but the school timing effect on willingness to commit to a property remains strong. Marketing should call out distance to the relevant private schools (in minutes by car) where the home is well placed for one or more of them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">International school and relocation considerations</h2>
      <p>For expats and interstate or international relocators, the school year may not align with the Queensland calendar at all. Some buyers will be moving on a different academic cycle entirely (Northern Hemisphere, mid-year start dates, etc.) and the standard October listing logic may not apply. Be flexible if the buyer's school timing differs and treat the relocation buyer pool as a useful supplement to (not a substitute for) the local family pool. Where the property is well placed for a corporate relocation buyer, the agent's marketing should include reach to relocation networks and to relevant employer HR teams.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do as a seller</h2>
      <p>Do not list a family home in mid-December and expect a strong family-buyer response, because the buyer pool is on holiday and the campaign timing works against itself. Do not assume that school timing is the only factor in family buyer decisions, because partner job moves, finance approvals, sale of the existing home, and personal circumstances all interact with the school calendar. Do not over-emphasise school catchment in marketing if the property is not actually in catchment, because the misrepresentation is easily uncovered and damages buyer trust. Do not list outside the family windows in the hope that a family will arrive anyway, because the better strategy in those off-windows is to target the buyer pool that is actually active rather than wait for one that is not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical framework</h2>
      <p>For family-targeted homes in Brisbane's inner east, the October to November listing window typically produces the strongest results, with March to May as a secondary option. For catchment-zone properties, this effect is amplified and the right window can be the difference between a competitive campaign and a flat one. For non-family-targeted homes (one-bedroom apartments, townhouses with limited storage, properties unsuitable for families), school timing matters less and other factors (interest rates, market sentiment, local supply) become dominant. The right approach is to ask early in the planning conversation: "Who is most likely to buy this home?" and to calibrate the listing date based on that answer rather than on a generic calendar rule.</p>

